\begin_layout Chapter
Inclusive Lepton-Nucleon Scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the process of the lepton scattering, the reaction is divided into several
 classes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The inclusive scattering only refers to measure the scattered lepton.
 This is the simplest way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The semi-inclusive scattering refers to measure the scattered lepton and
 one or more final-state particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The exclusive scattering refers to measure the scattered lepton, nucleon
 and all the reconstructed final particle produced in the interaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we only focus on the inclusive scattering.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Kinematic variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lowest order inclusive diagram for the lepton-nucleon scattering is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
l(p)+N(P)\rightarrow l(p')+X(P').\label{eq:lpscat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The diagram is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Feynman-DIS"

\end_inset

.
 For the fixed-target, the cross section for the scattering of leptons is
 dominated by virtual photon exchange.
 We denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $k'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

) are the initial (final) four-momentum and spin four-vector of the lepton,
 respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $q=k-k'$
\end_inset

 is the transferred four-momentum from the lepton to the nucleon, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the nucleon mass, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are the nucleon four-momentum and spin four-vector, respectively.
