\begin_layout Standard
In elastic scattering the nucleon remain in the ground state.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is not high enough so that the nucleus stays intact.
 The invariant mass 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is equal to the mass of the nucleon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quasi-elastic scattering happened when the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is higher than the nuclear binding energy.
 The nucleon is knocked out of the nucleus and can be considered as quasi-free.
 The energy shift of the quasi-elastic peak is because of the energy absorption
 for the nucleon remove from the nucleus.
 If the target is nucleon like a proton target, then there is no quasi-elastic
 peak.
