\begin_layout Standard
As the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 increase, the nucleon is excited to several different states known as the
 resonance region, which shows the composite structure system of the nucleon.
 The kinematic range of resonance is usually at 
\begin_inset Formula $1.0\ <\ W\ <\ 2.0\ GeV^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Several peaks in the resonance region show the different states of the
 nucleon.
 The first peak is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(1232)$
\end_inset

 resonance.
 The second peak consists of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N(1520)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(1535)$
\end_inset

 resonances.
 The third peak becomes more complicate since it contains many states.
 Also there is 
\begin_inset Formula $N(1440)$
\end_inset

 resonance exists between the peak of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(1232)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(1520)$
\end_inset

.
 The properties of each resonance states such like the invariant mass (
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

), width (
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

), total angular momentum (
\begin_inset Formula $J^{P}$
\end_inset

