\begin_layout Section
Differential cross section and structure functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering of one photon exchange for detecting the final lepton in the
 solid angle 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Omega$
\end_inset

 and final energy range (
\begin_inset Formula $E'$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $E'+dE'$
\end_inset

), the differential cross section can be written as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Anselmino:1994gn"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}\sigma}{d\Omega dE'}=\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2Mq^{4}}\frac{E'}{E}L_{\mu\nu}W^{\mu\nu},\label{eq:differentxsLW}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the electromagnetic coupling constant.
 The cross-section contains two part: The leptonic tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and the hadronic tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is known exactly and is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{\mu\nu}(k,s;k',s')=[\bar{u}(k',s')\gamma_{\mu}u(k,s)]^{*}[\bar{u}(k',s')\gamma_{\mu}u(k,s)],\label{eq:Luv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(k,s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}(k',s')$
\end_inset

 are electron spinors.
 The leptonic tensor can be split into symmetry part (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) and anti-symmetry part (
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) by interchanging the Lorentz indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and on summing over 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L_{\mu\nu}(k,s,k') & =L_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}(k;k')+iL_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}(k,s;k'),\label{eq:luvSA}\\
L_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}(k;k') & =2[k_{\mu}k_{\nu}'+k_{\mu}'k_{\nu}-g_{\mu\nu}(kk'-m^{2})],\\
L_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}(k,s;k') & =2[m\epsilon_{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}s^{\alpha}q^{\beta}],
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the metric tensor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}$
\end_inset

 is the Levi-Civita tensor.
 The Leptonic tensor is easy to calculate by using the QED formalism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hadronic tensor describes the interaction between the virtual photon
 and the nucleon, it is complicated to calculate directly.
 Four structure functions: unpolarized structure functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the spin related structure functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are used to parametrize the quantity.
 The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 can also be split into symmetry and anti-symmetry part:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{\mu\nu}(q;P,s)=W_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}(q;P)+iW_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}(q;P,s),\label{eq:Wuv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the symmetry part is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2M}W_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}(q;P)=(-g_{\mu\nu}+\frac{q_{\mu}q_{\nu}}{q^{2}})W_{1}(\nu,Q^{2})+[(P_{\mu}-\frac{P\cdot q}{q^{2}}q_{\mu})(P_{\nu}-\frac{P\cdot q}{q^{2}}q_{\nu})]\frac{W_{2}(\nu,Q^{2})}{M^{2}},\label{eq:WuvSW1W2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the anti-symmetry is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2M}W_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}(q;P,s)=\epsilon_{\mu\nu\alpha\beta}q^{\alpha}\{MS^{\beta}G_{1}(\nu,Q^{2})+[(P\cdot q)S^{\beta}-(S\cdot q)P^{\beta}]\frac{G_{2}(\nu,Q^{2})}{M}\},\label{eq:WuvAG1G2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:luvSA"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Wuv"

\end_inset

), the differential cross section can be rewritten as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}\sigma}{d\Omega dE'}=\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2Mq^{4}}\frac{E'}{E}[L_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}W^{\mu\nu(S)}-L_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}W^{\mu\nu(A)}].\label{eq:differentxsLWAS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It can be separately studied by considering the symmetry part 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}W_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}$
\end_inset

 and the anti-symmetry part 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}W_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}$
\end_inset

.
 The symmetry part is proportional to the unpolarized cross-section:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{unpol}}{d\Omega dE'}(k;P;k') & =2\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2Mq^{4}}\frac{E'}{E}L_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}W_{\mu\nu}^{(S)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{4\alpha^{2}E'^{2}}{q^{4}}[2W_{1}sin^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}+W_{2}cos^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}],\label{eq:unpoldiffxs}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}(P\cdot q,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}(P\cdot q,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 are the unpolarized structure functions.
 Note that the lepton mass is ignored.
 The anti-symmetry part can be extracted by using the differences of cross-secti
ons with opposite target or beam spins:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\frac{d^{2}\sigma}{d\Omega dE'}(k,s,P,S;k')-\frac{d^{2}\sigma}{d\Omega dE'}(k,s,P,-S;k')]=\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2Mq^{4}}\frac{E'}{E}L_{\mu\nu}^{(A)}W^{\mu\nu(A)}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & =\frac{8m\alpha^{2}E'}{q^{4}E}\{[(q\cdot S)(q\cdot s)+Q^{2}(s\cdot S)]MG_{1}+Q^{2}[(s\cdot S)(P\cdot q)-(q\cdot S)(P\cdot s)]\frac{G_{2}}{M}\},\label{eq:poldiffxs}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}(P\cdot q,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}(P\cdot q,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 are two polarized structure functions.
 For the longitudinally polarized case, the spin of the initial lepton is
 along with or opposite to the nucleon polarization.
 One obtains:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\sigma_{\Vert}=\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{\overrightarrow{\Rightarrow}}}{d\Omega dE'}-\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{\overrightarrow{\Leftarrow}}}{d\Omega dE'}=-\frac{4\alpha^{2}}{Q^{2}}\frac{E'}{E}[(E+E'cos\theta)MG_{1}-Q^{2}G_{2}].\label{eq:dxslong}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the transversely polarized case, the nucleon spin is perpendicular to
 the spin direction of the incoming lepton, and the azimuthal angle between
 the scattering plane (the plane between the incoming and outgoing lepton
 direction) and the polarization plane (the plane between the incoming lepton
 direction and the target polarization direction) is 0, one obtains:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\sigma_{\bot}=\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{\rightarrow\Uparrow}}{d\Omega dE'}-\frac{d^{2}\sigma^{\rightarrow\Downarrow}}{d\Omega dE'}=-\frac{4\alpha^{2}}{Q^{2}}\frac{E'^{2}}{E}sin\theta[MG_{1}+2EG_{2}].\label{eq:dxstran}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the deep inelastic region, with the Bjorken limit of: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q^{2}\rightarrow\infty,\ \nu\rightarrow\infty,\ and\ x\ fixed,\label{eq:bjorkenlimit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the structure functions 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}$
\end_inset

 are known to approximately scale 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRev.179.1547"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\underset{Bj}{lim}MW_{1}(P\cdot q,Q^{2}) & = & F_{1}(x),\label{eq:f1}\\
\underset{Bj}{lim}\nu W_{2}(P\cdot q,Q^{2}) & = & F_{2}(x),\label{eq:f2}\\
\underset{Bj}{lim}\frac{(P\cdot q)^{2}}{\nu}G_{1}(P\cdot q,Q^{2}) & = & g_{1}(x),\label{eq:g1}\\
\underset{Bj}{lim}\nu(P\cdot q)G_{2}(P\cdot q,Q^{2}) & = & g_{2}(x),\label{eq:g2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 vary very slow with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, which means in the Bjorken limit the 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 are only the function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 From the naive quark-parton model, the energy of the virtual photon is
 totally absorbed by the quark when 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is equal to the momentum of the quark-parton, which is definitely independent
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

.
  The experiments also confirmed that they are independent with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 in a large 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 range.
 But later on people found that the Bjorken scale will be failed in the
 region of smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 value 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.12.1884"

\end_inset

, which needs to consider the gluon contribution using the QCD correction.
 The structure function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 are then extended to 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1,2}(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1,2}(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
g_{1}(x,Q^{2}) & = & M^{2}\nu G_{1}(\nu,Q^{2}),\label{eq:g1G1}\\
g_{2}(x,Q^{2}) & = & M\nu^{2}G_{2}(\nu,Q^{2}),\label{eq:g2G2}\\
F_{1}(x,Q^{2}) & = & MW_{1}(\nu,Q^{2}),\label{eq:F1W1}\\
F_{2}(x,Q^{2}) & = & \nu W_{2}(\nu,Q^{2}).\label{eq:F2W2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unpoldiffxs"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dxslong"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dxstran"

\end_inset

) are then expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
d\sigma_{unpol}=\frac{d^{2}\sigma_{unpol}}{d\Omega dE'} & = & (\frac{d\sigma}{d\Omega})_{Mott}[\frac{2}{M}F_{1}(x,Q^{2})tan^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}+\frac{1}{\nu}F_{2}(x,Q^{2})],\label{eq:dxsunpol2}\\
(\frac{d\sigma}{d\Omega})_{Mott} & = & \frac{\alpha^{2}cos^{2}\frac{\theta}{2}}{4E^{2}sin^{4}\frac{\theta}{2}},\label{eq:mott}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta\sigma_{\Vert} & =-\frac{4\alpha^{2}E'}{MQ^{2}E\nu}[(E+E'cos\theta)g_{1}(x,Q^{2})-2Mxg_{2}(x,Q^{2})],\label{eq:dxslong2}\\
\Delta\sigma_{\bot} & =-\frac{4\alpha^{2}E'^{2}}{MQ^{2}E\nu}sin\theta[g_{1}(x,Q^{2})+\frac{2E}{\nu}g_{2}(x,Q^{2})],\label{eq:dxstran2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{d\sigma}{d\Omega})_{Mott}$
\end_inset

 is the Mott cross section, which describes the cross section when assuming
 the nucleon is a point-like particle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes it is more convenient to measure the asymmetries than the cross
 sections in order to avoid some system error, which are ratios of the cross
 section difference to the unpolarized cross section.
 The longitudinal asymmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 and the transverse asymmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\bot}$
\end_inset

 are expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{\Vert}=\frac{\Delta\sigma_{\Vert}}{2d\sigma_{unpol}},\label{eq:asymlong}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{\bot}=\frac{\Delta\sigma_{\bot}}{2d\sigma_{unpol}}.\label{eq:asymtran}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Virtual photoabsorption cross section
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the inelastic scattering of polarized electrons off polarized
 target nucleons, the differential cross section can be expressed with the
 virtual photon absorption cross section.
 In the deep-inelastic region, it is a process that the quark absorb the
 virtual photon, as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vphoton"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pic/vphoton.png
	lyxscale 30
	width 60col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:vphoton"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The interaction between the virtual photon and the polarized nucleon
\end_layout

\end_inset

The interaction between the virtual photon and the polarized nucleon 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yeprogressphys"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 We denote the longitudinal polarization of the incoming electrons as 
\begin_inset Formula $h=\pm1$
\end_inset

, and two polarization component of the target polarization as 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{x}$
\end_inset

 are parallel and perpendicular to the lab momentum of the virtual photon,
 respectively.
 The differential cross section for the absorption of the virtual photon
 can be express in terms of a virtual photon flux factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{v}$
\end_inset

 and four partial cross sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drechsel200399,PhysRevD.63.114010"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{d\sigma}{d\Omega dE'} & =\varGamma_{v}\sigma(\nu,Q^{2}),\label{eq:diffxsphotoabsorption}\\
\sigma & =\sigma_{T}+\epsilon\sigma_{L}+hP_{x}\sqrt{2\epsilon(1-\epsilon)}\sigma'_{LT}+hP_{z}\sqrt{1-\epsilon^{2}}\sigma'_{TT}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the flux factor:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{v}=\frac{\alpha}{2\pi}\frac{E'}{E}\frac{K}{Q^{2}}\frac{1}{1-\epsilon},\label{eq:Gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and its transverse polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon=\frac{1}{1+2(1+\frac{\nu^{2}}{Q^{2}})tan^{2}(\frac{\theta}{2})}.\label{eq:epsilon}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equivalent photon energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the laboratory photon energy producing a final state of total center-of-mass
 energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 upon absorption by a proton at rest defined by Hand 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRev.129.1834"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K=\nu(1-x)=\frac{(W^{2}-M^{2})}{2M}.\label{eq:K}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{L}$
\end_inset

 are for the unpolarized experiment, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'_{LT}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'_{TT}$
\end_inset

 are for the double polarization experiment.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'_{TT}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in terms of the helicity cross sections 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{3/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1/2}$
\end_inset

, which are corresponded to excitation of intermediate states with spin
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{3}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{T} & =\frac{1}{2}(\sigma_{3/2}+\sigma_{1/2}),\\
\sigma'_{TT} & =\frac{1}{2}(\sigma_{3/2}-\sigma_{1/2}).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The four virtual photoabsorption cross sections are related to the structure
 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1,2}$
\end_inset

, which depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{T} & =\frac{4\pi^{2}\alpha}{MK}F_{1},\label{eq:sigmaT}\\
\sigma_{L} & =\frac{4\pi^{2}\alpha}{K}(\frac{1+\gamma^{2}}{\gamma^{2}\nu}F_{2}-\frac{1}{M}F_{1}),\label{eq:sigmaL}\\
\sigma_{TT} & =\frac{4\pi^{2}\alpha}{MK}(g_{1}-\gamma^{2}g_{2}),\label{eq:sigmaLT}\\
\sigma_{LT} & =\frac{4\pi^{2}\alpha}{MK}\gamma(g_{1}+g_{2}).\label{eq:sigmaTT}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The virtual Compton scattering asymmetries, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, are defined by the helicity dependent virtual photon-nucleon scattering
 cross sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "robertsprotonstructure,leaderintroduction"

\end_inset

.
 For spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 targets (proton and neutron), the longitudinal asymmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 is expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{1}(x,Q^{2})=\frac{\sigma_{1/2}-\sigma_{3/2}}{\sigma_{1/2}+\sigma_{3/2}}.\label{eq:A1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the transverse asymmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 is expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{2}(x,Q^{2})=\frac{2\sigma_{LT}}{\sigma_{1/2}+\sigma_{3/2}}.\label{eq:A2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is customary to have the relationship between the virtual photon asymmetries
 and the structure functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
A_{1}(x,Q^{2}) & =\frac{\sigma_{TT}}{\sigma_{T}}=\frac{g_{1}(x,Q^{2})-\gamma^{2}g_{2}(x,Q^{2})}{F_{1}},\label{eq:A1g12}\\
A_{2}(x,Q^{2}) & =\frac{\sigma_{LT}}{\sigma_{T}}=\gamma(\frac{g_{1}(x,Q^{2})+g_{2}(x,Q^{2})}{F_{1}(x,Q^{2})}),\label{eq:A2g12}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{2Mx}{Q}=\frac{Q}{\nu}.\label{eq:gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The asymmetries 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\Vert}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\bot}$
\end_inset

 are expressed in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 following by equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dxsunpol2"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dxslong2"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dxstran2"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
A_{\Vert} & =D(A_{1}+\eta A_{2}),\label{eq:AlongA1A2}\\
A_{\bot} & =d(A_{2}-\xi A_{1}),\label{eq:AtranA1A2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
D & =\frac{y[(1+\frac{\gamma^{2}y}{2})(2-y)-\frac{2y^{2}m^{2}}{Q^{2}}]}{y^{2}(1-\frac{2m^{2}}{Q^{2}})(1+\gamma^{2})+2(1+R)(1-y-\frac{\gamma^{2}y^{2}}{4})},\label{eq:D}\\
d & =D\cdot\frac{[1+\frac{\gamma^{2}y}{2}(1+\frac{2m^{2}y}{Q^{2}})]\sqrt{1-y-\frac{\gamma^{2}y^{2}}{4}}}{(1-\frac{y}{2})(1+\frac{\gamma^{2}y}{2})-\frac{y^{2}m^{2}}{Q^{2}}},\label{eq:d}\\
\eta & =\gamma\frac{[1-y-y^{2}(\frac{\gamma^{2}}{4}+\frac{m^{2}}{Q^{2}})]}{(1-\frac{y}{2})(1+\frac{\gamma^{2}y}{2})-\frac{y^{2}m^{2}}{Q^{2}}},\label{eq:eta}\\
\xi & =\gamma\frac{1-\frac{y}{2}-\frac{y^{2}m^{2}}{Q^{2}}}{1+\frac{\gamma^{2}y}{2}(1+\frac{2m^{2}y}{Q^{2}})},\label{eq:xi}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the ratio of the longitudinal and transverse cross section:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R=\frac{\sigma_{L}}{\sigma_{T}}=(1+\gamma^{2})(\frac{F_{2}}{2xF_{1}})-1.\label{eq:R}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

When ignoring the mass of lepton with a small 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{2}$
\end_inset

, it becomes to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevD.58.112003"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
D & =\frac{1-E'\epsilon/E}{1+\epsilon R},\\
d & =D\sqrt{\frac{2\epsilon}{1+\epsilon}},\\
\eta & =\frac{\epsilon\sqrt{Q^{2}}}{(E-E'\epsilon)},\\
\xi & =\frac{\eta(1+\epsilon)}{2\epsilon}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be extracted by measuring the longitudinal asymmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 and the transverse asymmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\bot}$
\end_inset

 using the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:asymlong"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:asymtran"

\end_inset

).
 The structure functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 can then be extracted from the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:A1g12"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:A2g12"

\end_inset

).
 With a series of measurement in different 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

, we can obtain the first moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}(Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{2}(Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 with the structure functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(x,Q^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\bot}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are much smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the DIS region, thus the measurement needs more accuracy.
 In the high 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}$
\end_inset

 region the term of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 is suppressed due to the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{2}$
\end_inset

, the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:A1g12"

\end_inset

) can be simplified as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}=g_{1}/F_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Many experiments used this method to extract 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 without measuring the transverse polarized cross section.
 But there is not enough reason to ignore the term of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For safety it is necessary to make a limit of it.
 There is a well-known condition established from the quark-parton model:
 
\begin_inset Formula $|A_{2}|\leq\sqrt{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Later on people found that there exists a strong bound between 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Soffer:1999zv"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|A_{2}|\leq\sqrt{R(1+A_{1})/2}.\label{eq:A1A2bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

